{event text}
{Color 08}Wiegraf{Newline}
{Color 00}Your faces are known to me. But I did not know{Newline}
that you would one day kill my sister.{Newline}
Milleuda deserved a better death—they did not{Newline}
even send proper knights to kill her!
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}She was your sister...{Newline}
I am sorry.
{MClose}
I will not flee before her murderers. I'll venge{Newline}
Milleuda's death or die in the trying!
{MClose}
{Color 08}Delita{Newline}
{Color 00}My sister, Tietra—you will set her free!
{MClose}
{Color 08}Wiegraf{Newline}
{Color 00}Your sister? Then you are a Beoulve, yes?
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}He is not. If it is a Beoulve you{Newline}
seek, address yourself to me!
{MClose}
So, Gragoroth has erred. But surely{Newline}
the girl must hold some connection{Newline}
with House Beoulve?
{MClose}
You draw no distinction between our{Newline}
house and those who deal with us?
{MClose}
Should I?{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Well, it matters not. There was no{Newline}
question as to her release. We make{Newline}
no habit of holding hostages.{Newline}
But first we've a score to settle.{Newline}
You will see her free—if you live{Newline}
to see aught at all!
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}Lay down your arms, Wiegraf!{Newline}
What end will more deaths serve?
{MClose}
{Color 08}Wiegraf{Newline}
{Color 00}What end did my sister's death serve?
{MClose}
We did not set out to kill her!{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
This quarrel need not be settled by{Newline}
the sword. Let us treat, and persist{Newline}
not in this bloodshed!
{MClose}
You see it not—the reason we hold fast to{Newline}
our steel!{Newline}
{Newline}
What advantage might I hope to enjoy at the{Newline}
treaty table? And who would set a seat for{Newline}
me there? You?{Newline}
Even were it in your power, your brothers{Newline}
would never heed any agreement we might{Newline}
reach!
{MClose}
My brothers do not want this fight!{Newline}
Set down your sword, Wiegraf, and{Newline}
my brothers will treat with you!
{MClose}
Ha! No spoony bard could spin a sweeter{Newline}
tale!{Newline}
{Newline}
You say your brothers do not want this{Newline}
fight? Tears then, for the world you see{Newline}
is one beyond my weary sight.
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}You would have me believe my brothers{Newline}
plot at war?
{MClose}
{Color 08}Wiegraf{Newline}
{Color 00}Callow child. The hands that guide history's{Newline}
reins are ever black with blood.{Newline}
Think you Dycedarg's hand more just?{Newline}
A new justice is born and dies on the lips{Newline}
of each man who would pronounce it.
{MClose}
Do not mock my brothers!
{MClose}
{Color 08}Wiegraf{Newline}
{Color 00}You fight well, boy.{Newline}
{Newline}
Forgive me, Milleuda! But there is too much{Newline}
left undone for me to lay down my life now.
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}Wiegraf, wait!
{MClose}
Who do you think sent Gustav to{Newline}
kidnap Marquis Elmdore?{Newline}
{Newline}
It was none other than your lord{Newline}
brother, Dycedarg. With Lord{Newline}
Zalbaag's approval, to be sure.
{MClose}
Absurd! Why would Dycedarg{Newline}
do such a thing?
{MClose}
The Lions vie for power in the void left by{Newline}
the king's death.{Newline}
{Newline}
I speak, of course, of Larg, the White Lion,{Newline}
and Goltanna, the Black.{Newline}
{Newline}
Each hopes to learn who may be counted{Newline}
as friend, and who as foe. But such things{Newline}
are not so easily read.{Newline}
Easier rid yourself of those whose loyalty is{Newline}
uncertain, and install others to rule in their{Newline}
stead.{Newline}
I fear Gustav, fool that he was, tired of our{Newline}
rebellion, and was taken in by the silver{Newline}
tongue of your dear brother, Dycedarg.
{MClose}
Lies! No Beoulve would do a thing{Newline}
so craven as this!
{MClose}
Do not take my word for it. Judge their actions{Newline}
for yourself. Farewell, young Beoulve.
{MClose}
Wiegraf! Coward! You insult my name,{Newline}
and flee in the same breath!
{MClose}
