{Color 08}Knight Templar Barich{Newline}
{Color 00}That's the last of it. The winds bear{Newline}
it onward now.{Newline}
And fair winds they are. They should{Newline}
keep it airborne for a half-day if they{Newline}
hold—more than time enough.
{MClose}
Now there is a creature I had not{Newline}
thought to find in these wastes!
{MClose}
One might say the same of a Knight{Newline}
Templar so far from the Church.{Newline}
{Newline}
What is it you scatter to the wind?
{MClose}
Oh, that?{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
I suppose there's no harm in your{Newline}
knowing. There's naught you can{Newline}
do to stop it now.
{MClose}
Stop what!?
{MClose}
This.
{MClose}
Poison!
{MClose}
Yes. Ground into a fine powder and cast{Newline}
upon the winds toward the Northern Sky.{Newline}
{Newline}
The toxin will not kill the men who breathe{Newline}
it—but it will wither their constitution,{Newline}
rendering them unable to fight.
{MClose}
But why? The High Confessor stands{Newline}
to gain naught by handing victory to{Newline}
Goltanna!
{MClose}
Nor does he think to.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
The moment Goltanna hears of the{Newline}
Northern Order's plight, he will send his{Newline}
armies against them.{Newline}
With his own stronghold unguarded, Goltanna{Newline}
will be an easy target for assassination, and{Newline}
Count Orlandeau with him.{Newline}
But do not think Duke Larg will escape this{Newline}
scourge—his is the easy death to achieve.{Newline}
{Newline}
Amidst the coming chaos, who could say{Newline}
how Duke Larg might meet his end?{Newline}
{MClose}
You're inhuman!
{MClose}
You ought rejoice! This will mean{Newline}
an end to war and bloodshed.{Newline}
{Newline}
And with that end, a new beginning.{Newline}
The Church's hand shall rule. Such{Newline}
is the will of the people.{Newline}
They clamor for change—an end to{Newline}
groveling at highborn heels.
{MClose}
The war will end, but not like this.{Newline}
There is another way!
{MClose}
I expected you'd say as much—no matter!
{MClose}
{Color 08}Barich{Newline}
{Color 00}Once you've put a stop to this{Newline}
fighting, what then?{Newline}
How do you propose to purge{Newline}
Ivalice of her corruption?{Newline}
{Newline}
Her fever will not cease to rage till{Newline}
her festered limbs are cut and seared!{Newline}
Even you must see that now!
{MClose}
{Color 08}{Ramza}{Newline}
{Color 00}You would cut away the pure flesh with{Newline}
the foul.{Newline}
There is corruption, yes, but there are{Newline}
also good men in Ivalice, and they are{Newline}
not few!{Newline}
There are ways to heal a festered{Newline}
wound without the knife. The poison{Newline}
can be drawn!
{MClose}
Pray tell what poultice might draw{Newline}
the nobles from this land!{Newline}
{Newline}
So long as you blight it with your{Newline}
existence, we must bow to your{Newline}
whims.{Newline}
A man alone might know equality.{Newline}
Two men, never! One will ever seek{Newline}
to exploit the other.{Newline}
And I will not be exploited! I will{Newline}
claim your seat, and take what is{Newline}
my due.{Newline}
I should think I have at least that right!
{MClose}
You think to cure the realm's corruption{Newline}
by becoming part of it?{Newline}
{Newline}
What when another comes to claim your{Newline}
seat? You care not for Ivalice's suffering—{Newline}
you care only for your own!
{MClose}
Such righteous words! More the{Newline}
greater your hypocrisy!
{MClose}
{Color 08}Barich{Newline}
{Color 00}No! I was not...not{Newline}
to die like this...
