{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin our lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session, we shall delve into how to{Newline}
control your units on the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
Since the battlefield is a three-dimensional{Newline}
environment, you may view it from a{Newline}
variety of angles.{Newline}
Use the L and R buttons and the analog stick{Newline}
to adjust your view of the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
The analog stick rotates your view of{Newline}
the battlefield.
{MClose}
The L button zooms the camera in and out,{Newline}
and the R button toggles the camera height.
{MClose}
Try using these controls now.{Newline}
Press START when you are finished.
{MClose}
You may also scroll across the screen by holding{Newline}
down □ and using the directional buttons.{Newline}
{Newline}
Try it now, and press START when finished.
{MClose}
You will need to master these controls if you{Newline}
want to be aware of what is occurring on{Newline}
the battlefield.{Newline}
Next, we will cover the battlefield cursor.
{MClose}
The battlefield cursor is used to select units{Newline}
or tiles on the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
The cursor's height (h) is displayed in the upper{Newline}
right corner of the screen, and the selected{Newline}
unit's status is displayed at the bottom.{Newline}
Press ○ to close the menu, then use the{Newline}
directional buttons to move the battlefield{Newline}
cursor.{Newline}
Press START when you are finished.
{MClose}
The cursor is used to select a unit's{Newline}
movement destination or attack target.{Newline}
{Newline}
Battlefields are often made up of complex{Newline}
terrain, and some locations may be inaccessible.{Newline}
{Newline}
The cursor is normally blue, but it will turn red{Newline}
when moved over a tile inaccessible to the unit.{Newline}
{Newline}
You now know the basics of controlling the{Newline}
battlefield cursor.{Newline}
{Newline}
Let us move on to something a bit more{Newline}
advanced.{Newline}
{Newline}
Sometimes you will encounter tiles that are{Newline}
above other ones.{Newline}
{Newline}
For example, you may be able to move over or{Newline}
under a bridge.
{MClose}
Allow me to explain how to use the cursor in{Newline}
a case like this.{Newline}
{Newline}
First, move the cursor to either the upper or{Newline}
lower tile, then wait after moving the cursor.{Newline}
{Newline}
It will automatically begin to toggle between{Newline}
the upper and lower tiles.
{MClose}
Simply make your selection when the cursor{Newline}
is on the correct tile.{Newline}
{Newline}
Try it now. Press START when you are{Newline}
finished.
{MClose}
You may adjust the speed of the cursor when{Newline}
switching between levels by using option 3,{Newline}
"Multi-height Toggle Rate."{Newline}
If this option is turned off, the cursor will{Newline}
not move automatically.{Newline}
{Newline}
Instead, you must press START to toggle{Newline}
between different levels.{Newline}
{Newline}
There are also two other special ways of{Newline}
moving the cursor, related to the units' turn{Newline}
order.{Newline}
To move the cursor automatically to the{Newline}
active unit, move the cursor to an empty{Newline}
tile and press ×.{Newline}
Repeatedly pressing START will cycle{Newline}
the cursor from unit to unit in turn order.{Newline}
{Newline}
This is useful for determining the order in{Newline}
which units will act.{Newline}
{Newline}
However, you cannot use this method if you{Newline}
are using START to switch between multiple{Newline}
levels.
{MClose}
Now allow me to explain the commands you may{Newline}
use when selecting a unit with the cursor.{Newline}
{Newline}
If you move the cursor to one of your units and{Newline}
press ×, the unit's battle menu will appear.
{MClose}
In addition, if you press ○ when a unit is{Newline}
selected by the cursor, that unit's range of{Newline}
movement will be displayed.
{MClose}
This concludes our discussion of the{Newline}
battlefield cursor.{Newline}
{Newline}
Using the cursor is one of the fundamentals{Newline}
of battle, so please do your best to remember{Newline}
what you have learned here.{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
