{event text}
{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session we shall explore the{Newline}
fundamentals of battle, from beginning to end.{Newline}
{Newline}
Firstly, you must select the units you wish to{Newline}
use in battle and position them on the field.{Newline}
{Newline}
The number of units you may use in battle{Newline}
varies depending upon the situation, but in{Newline}
general, you are limited to five.{Newline}
In some cases, you may need to split your{Newline}
units into two separate squads.{Newline}
{Newline}
If you always use the same units in battle,{Newline}
their advancement will soon outpace that of{Newline}
your other units.{Newline}
When selecting units to use in battle, keep{Newline}
in mind both their skills and their need for{Newline}
advancement.{Newline}
Sometimes allied units will appear in battle{Newline}
without your having selected them. These{Newline}
are known as guest units.
{MClose}
Guest units have their own agendas{Newline}
and will move and act on their own.
{MClose}
Once you have selected your units, you will{Newline}
move to the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
And then, battle will begin—but we are getting{Newline}
ahead of ourselves. First, we must discuss{Newline}
objectives.{Newline}
For example, this...
{MClose}
Or, this...
{MClose}
Messages such as these will appear as each{Newline}
battle begins, telling you what you must do{Newline}
in order to win.{Newline}
In general, you must defeat all of the enemies,{Newline}
but in some cases, you must fulfill other special{Newline}
conditions.
{MClose}
Once the battle has begun, each of your units{Newline}
will move and act in turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
When it is a unit's turn to move and act, he or{Newline}
she will be designated by the AT icon, which{Newline}
stands for Active Turn.{Newline}
A unit's turn comes when his or her charge{Newline}
time (CT) gauge reaches 100.{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit's Speed attribute determines how much{Newline}
his or her CT gauge fills with each tick of{Newline}
the game clock.{Newline}
During a unit's turn, he or she may move and{Newline}
perform actions such as attacking an enemy.{Newline}
{Newline}
Let's examine the battle menu, shall we?
{MClose}
The Move, Act, and Wait commands are{Newline}
displayed only when it is the unit's turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit may move once and act once during{Newline}
his or her turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
If the unit has both moved and performed{Newline}
an action, his or her turn will automatically{Newline}
come to an end.{Newline}
The Wait command is used to end the turn if{Newline}
the unit will only be moving or acting, or if he{Newline}
or she will do nothing.{Newline}
Next, let's examine the other commands.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Status allows you to check a unit's detailed{Newline}
status.
{MClose}
The AI command allows you to set an AI{Newline}
pattern for the unit so that it will decide{Newline}
its own actions.{Newline}
Units that use AI will move and fight{Newline}
automatically until the AI command is{Newline}
canceled.
{MClose}
You may select from four different AI{Newline}
strategies.{Newline}
{Newline}
Berserker will cause the unit to attack its{Newline}
target without regard for his or her own{Newline}
safety.{Newline}
Defender will cause the unit to protect a{Newline}
friendly target without regard for his or{Newline}
her own safety.{Newline}
Healer will cause the unit to focus upon{Newline}
restoring the HP and MP of allied units.{Newline}
{Newline}
Coward will cause the unit to attempt to{Newline}
escape to a safe location while recovering{Newline}
his or her own HP.{Newline}
For Berserker and Defender, you must{Newline}
select a target for the unit to attack or{Newline}
protect.{Newline}
Once a unit's AI has been enabled, that unit{Newline}
will fight automatically from then on.{Newline}
{Newline}
To cancel this setting, select the AI command{Newline}
and choose Manual.{Newline}
{Newline}
However, since the unit will be acting{Newline}
automatically, you cannot access the unit's{Newline}
menu on his or her own turn.{Newline}
You must cancel the setting during another{Newline}
unit's turn or after pausing the battle.
{MClose}
The Status and AI commands may be selected{Newline}
even if it is not the selected unit's turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
Normally, the menu will not appear for an{Newline}
enemy unit or a unit which has been set to{Newline}
use AI.{Newline}
However, you may halt the course of battle{Newline}
and force a menu to appear by pressing △.{Newline}
{Newline}
Doing so will open a menu on the next unit's{Newline}
turn.
{MClose}
This allows you to stop units using AI, or to{Newline}
view the status of enemy units.{Newline}
{Newline}
You will not be able to give commands{Newline}
to any of your units while the battle is{Newline}
stopped in this way.{Newline}
To resume the battle (assuming the current{Newline}
unit is not set to AI), select "Done."{Newline}
{Newline}
This command may be found at the{Newline}
bottom of the menu.
{MClose}
This concludes my overview of battle commands.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
To summarize, you may select "Move," "Act,"{Newline}
or "Wait" during a unit's turn, as well as check{Newline}
the unit's status.{Newline}
In some cases, you may wish to set an AI{Newline}
pattern for a unit. To resume the battle after{Newline}
it has been interrupted, select "Done."{Newline}
These are the main commands that you will{Newline}
use in the course of a battle.
{MClose}
Next is a most unpleasant subject.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
When a unit's HP reaches zero, the unit{Newline}
will be KO'd.
{MClose}
If you do not revive a KO'd unit within a{Newline}
certain amount of time, the unit's body{Newline}
will disappear.{Newline}
In its place, a treasure chest or crystal will{Newline}
appear.
{MClose}
Once a unit has disappeared in this way,{Newline}
there is no way of reviving it. The unit is{Newline}
gone forever.{Newline}
If one of your units is KO'd, do your best to{Newline}
revive him or her as quickly as possible.{Newline}
{Newline}
If all of your units are KO'd, the game is over.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Always keep an eye upon your units'{Newline}
remaining HP to prevent this from happening.{Newline}
{Newline}
I recommend that you always bring at least{Newline}
one unit who is capable of healing or reviving{Newline}
KO'd units.{Newline}
On the other hand, KO'ing all enemy units{Newline}
on the battlefield will end the battle, assuming{Newline}
you have fulfilled the battle objective.
{MClose}
This concludes our battle overview and my{Newline}
explanation of the battle menu.{Newline}
{Newline}
I trust you will make good use of this{Newline}
information on the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
The Status and AI commands may be selected{Newline}
even if it is not the selected unit's turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
Normally, the menu will not appear for an{Newline}
enemy unit or a unit which has been set to{Newline}
use AI.{Newline}
However, you may halt the course of battle{Newline}
and force a menu to appear by pressing △.{Newline}
{Newline}
Doing so will open a menu on the next unit's{Newline}
turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
This allows you to stop units using AI, or to{Newline}
view the status of enemy units.{Newline}
{Newline}
You will not be able to give commands{Newline}
to any of your units while the battle is{Newline}
stopped in this way.{Newline}
To resume the battle (assuming the current{Newline}
unit is not set to AI), select "Done."{Newline}
{Newline}
This command may be found at the{Newline}
bottom of the menu.
{MClose}
This concludes my overview of battle commands.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
