{event text}
{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session, I shall explain movement and{Newline}
actions.{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit is allowed one move and one action{Newline}
during his or her turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
Let's try controlling a unit as he moves{Newline}
and acts.{Newline}
{Newline}
First, you must move your unit to a tile{Newline}
next to the enemy you wish to attack.{Newline}
{Newline}
Try selecting "Move."
{MClose}
As you can see, the tiles around your unit are{Newline}
flashing blue.{Newline}
{Newline}
These blue tiles indicate the movement range{Newline}
of your unit. You must select a destination from{Newline}
among these tiles.{Newline}
But first, allow me to explain how a unit's{Newline}
movement range is determined.{Newline}
{Newline}
Each unit's range of movement is determined by{Newline}
his or her Move and Jump attributes.{Newline}
{Newline}
On flat terrain, a unit may move a number of{Newline}
tiles in one turn equal to the unit's Move{Newline}
attribute.{Newline}
So, if a unit's Move is 4, he or she may move{Newline}
4 tiles.{Newline}
{Newline}
Likewise, the unit may perform a vertical jump{Newline}
to a height equaling his or her Jump attribute.{Newline}
{Newline}
He or she may also jump horizontally for a{Newline}
distance equaling half his or her Jump attribute.{Newline}
{Newline}
So, a unit with a Jump of 3 could jump{Newline}
horizontally over a 1-tile gap, or jump up{Newline}
or down 3 levels.{Newline}
In this case, "levels" refer to the difference{Newline}
between the height of the unit's current tile and{Newline}
that of the target tile.{Newline}
Now then, let us continue practicing movement.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Once the unit's movement range is displayed,{Newline}
select a destination.{Newline}
{Newline}
If there is an allied chocobo on the tile you{Newline}
select, your unit will mount that chocobo.
{MClose}
Now try approaching the enemy by selecting{Newline}
the tile directly in front of him.
{MClose}
Since a unit may only move once per turn, the{Newline}
Move command is now grayed out and cannot{Newline}
be selected.{Newline}
Now try attacking with a weapon.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
To do this, you must select the Attack{Newline}
command.{Newline}
{Newline}
Try it now. Select "Act" and then "Attack."
{MClose}
The tiles around your unit have turned red.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
This indicates the unit's attack range.{Newline}
He may attack any unit on a red tile.{Newline}
{Newline}
Allow me to explain a bit about attack range.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit's attack range is determined by the{Newline}
weapon a unit has equipped, as well as his{Newline}
or her abilities.{Newline}
For example, a sword has a range of only one{Newline}
tile, but a bow allows a unit to extend his or{Newline}
her attack to tiles that are quite far away.{Newline}
Magicks generally have a long range as well.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Next, try selecting your target. Move the{Newline}
cursor to your enemy and press ×.
{MClose}
Notice that the enemy unit's tile has turned{Newline}
green.{Newline}
{Newline}
Green tiles indicate the attack's area of{Newline}
effect.{Newline}
{Newline}
The area of effect depends upon the weapon{Newline}
a unit has equipped, as well as his or her{Newline}
abilities.{Newline}
Most weapons have an area of effect of just{Newline}
one tile, but magicks may affect many tiles{Newline}
at once.{Newline}
The status of each unit is displayed at the{Newline}
bottom of the screen.{Newline}
{Newline}
On the left is the attacking unit, and on the{Newline}
right is his or her target.{Newline}
{Newline}
The attacking unit's turn order, level,{Newline}
and EXP are not shown here.{Newline}
{Newline}
In place of them, you will see an estimate{Newline}
of the attack's effect. The HP value listed{Newline}
here is the estimated amount of damage.{Newline}
To the right is the probability that{Newline}
the attack will succeed.{Newline}
{Newline}
By checking these, you can get a good idea of{Newline}
how effective an attack will be against a{Newline}
particular enemy.{Newline}
For standard attacks, only the damage{Newline}
estimate and chance of success are{Newline}
displayed.{Newline}
For magicks that cause status effects, the{Newline}
status effect's name and its chance of being{Newline}
inflicted will also be displayed.{Newline}
If the targeted unit has a reaction ability,{Newline}
the name of that ability will appear beneath{Newline}
the unit's status display.{Newline}
In battle, it is important to check all of{Newline}
these when choosing a target.{Newline}
{Newline}
You should also note that a unit's Bravery,{Newline}
Faith, and zodiac sign all affect the damage{Newline}
and success rate of attacks.{Newline}
A unit's Bravery also affects its bare-handed{Newline}
Attack attribute and the chance that its{Newline}
reaction ability will be triggered.{Newline}
Faith affects the damage and success rate{Newline}
of a unit's magick attacks.{Newline}
{Newline}
For example, a unit with high Faith inflicts{Newline}
more damage when casting Firaga, and is{Newline}
more like to successfully cast Raise.{Newline}
The relationship between the zodiac signs{Newline}
of the attacker and defender also affects{Newline}
damage and success rate.{Newline}
If the two signs are compatible, attacks{Newline}
will do more damage and healing magicks{Newline}
will be more effective.{Newline}
If the two signs are incompatible, damage{Newline}
will be reduced, as will the success rate{Newline}
of magicks.{Newline}
The estimated results of an attack take{Newline}
into account Faith, Bravery, and zodiac{Newline}
sign compatibility.{Newline}
Now then, let us continue by selecting the{Newline}
target.{Newline}
{Newline}
Once you have checked the area of effect{Newline}
and estimated results, you may confirm{Newline}
your target.{Newline}
Press × to confirm the selection.
{MClose}
If an attack is successful, the attacker will{Newline}
gain experience points (EXP) and job points{Newline}
(JP).{Newline}
After a unit has both moved and acted, {Newline}
his or her turn will automatically end.{Newline}
{Newline}
When a unit's turn ends, you must choose his or{Newline}
her facing. This affects the probability of the{Newline}
unit evading enemy attacks.{Newline}
You will want to be facing the enemy whenever{Newline}
possible.
{MClose}
That concludes my explanation of{Newline}
movement and actions.{Newline}
{Newline}
You shall be repeating these steps many times{Newline}
as you battle your foes.{Newline}
{Newline}
This is one of the fundamentals of battle, so{Newline}
please do your best to remember what you{Newline}
have learned here.{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
