{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session, we will discuss the CT gauge{Newline}
and how it relates to the order in which units{Newline}
take their turns.{Newline}
All units, be they enemy or ally, move and{Newline}
act in a certain order.{Newline}
{Newline}
The order in which units take their turns is{Newline}
determined by their charge time (CT).{Newline}
{Newline}
Once a unit's CT gauge fills up, that unit's{Newline}
turn has arrived.{Newline}
{Newline}
You may check a unit's charge time by looking{Newline}
at his or her CT gauge.{Newline}
{Newline}
The CT gauge is located below the unit's{Newline}
HP and MP.
{MClose}
This gauge, located at the bottom of a unit's{Newline}
status display in the lower left corner of the{Newline}
screen, represents his or her charge time.{Newline}
Once this gauge reaches 100, it is fully{Newline}
charged and it becomes the unit's turn to{Newline}
move and act.{Newline}
The CT gauges of all units fill with each tick{Newline}
of the game clock, but the rate at which{Newline}
they fill is different for each unit.{Newline}
Because of this, some units will see their{Newline}
turns come more quickly than others.{Newline}
{Newline}
Allow me to explain a bit more about how the{Newline}
CT gauge fills.
{MClose}
Here is the unit's status screen.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Look at the left side of the middle panel.{Newline}
You will see an attribute labeled Speed.
{MClose}
Allow me to give an example.
{MClose}
This unit has a Speed of 9.
{MClose}
This unit has a Speed of 6.
{MClose}
Let us observe how their CT gauges fill.
{MClose}
