sees his turn come earlier.{Newline}
{Newline}
Of course, in an actual battle, you do not{Newline}
have to wait while the CT gauges fill up.{Newline}
{Newline}
The active turn will automatically advance{Newline}
to whichever unit has the next turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
Now you know how the CT gauge works.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit's Speed is added to the gauge for{Newline}
each tick of the game clock, until the gauge{Newline}
reaches 100. Then it is the unit's turn.{Newline}
Thus, the higher a unit's Speed, the more{Newline}
often he or she will receive a turn.
{MClose}
Even understanding how the CT gauge{Newline}
controls turn order, it is difficult to keep{Newline}
track of the turn order for all units.{Newline}
So, I shall teach you a simple method of{Newline}
checking the turn order in battle.
{MClose}
Look at the status display at the bottom of the{Newline}
screen. There are two numbers to the upper right{Newline}
of the unit's portrait.{Newline}
The number to the left of the slash indicates{Newline}
that unit's turn order. The number to the right{Newline}
is the total number of units on the battlefield.{Newline}
Thus, to see an estimate of when a unit will get{Newline}
his or her turn, you merely have to move the{Newline}
cursor to the unit's tile and check this number.{Newline}
I say "estimate," because in some cases the{Newline}
CT gauge will be filled in an irregular fashion.{Newline}
{Newline}
In particular, I am referring to what happens{Newline}
when a unit chooses the Wait command.
{MClose}
A unit can use the Wait command when he{Newline}
or she only wants to move or act, or does{Newline}
not wish to do anything.{Newline}
Normally, when a unit's turn ends, the CT{Newline}
gauge resets to zero.{Newline}
{Newline}
But when a unit ends his or her turn by{Newline}
selecting "Wait," the gauge will start its{Newline}
next count from 20 or even 40.{Newline}
When a unit selects the command after{Newline}
moving or acting, the gauge will be reset{Newline}
to 20.{Newline}
When a unit chooses to wait without{Newline}
moving or acting at all, the gauge will{Newline}
be reset to 40.{Newline}
In other words, the time until the unit's next{Newline}
turn will be shortened.{Newline}
{Newline}
This may sometimes change the turn order{Newline}
of the units on the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
If you plan carefully, you can use the{Newline}
Wait command to your advantage.
{MClose}
This concludes my explanation of the CT{Newline}
gauge and turn order.{Newline}
{Newline}
Let us review.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
A unit's turn comes when his or her CT gauge{Newline}
reaches 100.{Newline}
{Newline}
With every tick of the game clock, a unit's{Newline}
CT gauge increases by an amount equal to{Newline}
the unit's Speed attribute.{Newline}
Thus, the higher a unit's Speed, the more{Newline}
often he or she will receive a turn.{Newline}
{Newline}
Understanding these concepts should allow you{Newline}
to gain the upper hand in any battle.{Newline}
{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
Every time the CT gauge is incremented, the{Newline}
value increases by an amount equal to the{Newline}
unit's Speed.{Newline}
This means that units with a high Speed will{Newline}
see their CT gauges fill more quickly.
{MClose}
