{event text}
{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session we shall discuss how to use{Newline}
magicks.{Newline}
{Newline}
As with units, each magick has a charge time,{Newline}
which starts when a unit begins to cast it,{Newline}
and ends when the magick goes into effect.{Newline}
Each magick also has a Speed attribute that{Newline}
affects how quickly it charges.{Newline}
{Newline}
The charge time for magicks begins when a{Newline}
unit starts to cast them.{Newline}
{Newline}
If the unit's next turn arrives before the{Newline}
casting is complete, the unit cannot perform{Newline}
another action without canceling the magick.{Newline}
If the unit chooses the Wait command, it will{Newline}
continue casting. The unit may also move{Newline}
without interrupting the casting.{Newline}
Perhaps the easiest way to learn about magick{Newline}
is to actually use it.{Newline}
{Newline}
First, select "Act" from the unit's menu.
{MClose}
Now select "Black Magicks."
{MClose}
The black magicks available to this unit{Newline}
are displayed.{Newline}
{Newline}
Magicks that are marked with the ☇ icon{Newline}
may be reflected with the Reflect ability.{Newline}
{Newline}
The MP cost of casting the magick is shown{Newline}
in the column labeled "MP."{Newline}
{Newline}
The "Turn" column indicates when the magick{Newline}
will actually go into effect.{Newline}
{Newline}
All magicks require time to cast.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
The Turn value tells you when the unit{Newline}
will finish casting the magick in the{Newline}
current turn order.{Newline}
It is calculated based on the casting{Newline}
unit's turn order and the amount of time{Newline}
it takes to cast the magick.{Newline}
You can press the left or right button to{Newline}
see more detailed information.{Newline}
{Newline}
Move the cursor to the spell whose timing{Newline}
you wish to check, and press the left or{Newline}
right button now.
{MClose}
Empty
{MClose}
The turn list is displayed. The flashing row{Newline}
with the casting unit's name and the magick's{Newline}
name indicates when the magick will be cast.{Newline}
This list may also be viewed at any time by{Newline}
pressing △ and selecting "Turn List."{Newline}
{Newline}
Now press ○ to return to the spell selection{Newline}
menu.
{MClose}
For now, try casting the first spell{Newline}
on the list.
{MClose}
The red tiles around the unit indicate the{Newline}
magick's range.{Newline}
{Newline}
You may select any of these tiles as the{Newline}
target.{Newline}
{Newline}
The targeted unit or units will be damaged{Newline}
by offensive magicks, or aided by support{Newline}
magicks.{Newline}
Select that enemy unit's tile as your target.
{MClose}
The green tiles around the target indicate{Newline}
the magick's area of effect.{Newline}
{Newline}
Any units within the the area of effect{Newline}
will be affected.{Newline}
{Newline}
Since you are casting an offensive magick,{Newline}
units in the area of effect will be damaged.{Newline}
{Newline}
Note that allied units and enemy units will{Newline}
flash in different colors to help you{Newline}
distinguish friend from foe.{Newline}
Note that both allies and enemies can be{Newline}
damaged by your magicks.{Newline}
{Newline}
Therefore, you should always ensure that{Newline}
there are no blue flashing units in the{Newline}
area of effect.{Newline}
You may turn off the flashing color effect{Newline}
with option 10, "Target Colors."{Newline}
{Newline}
Press × again to confirm your target.
{MClose}
Next, choose whether you wish to target the{Newline}
unit or the tile beneath him.{Newline}
{Newline}
If you select "Unit," that unit will remain{Newline}
the magick's target, even if he or she moves{Newline}
while it is being cast.{Newline}
If you select "Tile" and the unit moves{Newline}
while the magick is being cast, the magick{Newline}
will be cast upon the empty tile.{Newline}
Choosing "Unit" ensures that a magick will affect{Newline}
the targeted unit. But if the unit moves, the{Newline}
magick may then affect your own units as well.{Newline}
This time, let's select the unit as our target.
{MClose}
Only one magick may be cast at a time. Starting{Newline}
another action before the initial magick has{Newline}
been cast will cancel it.{Newline}
This concludes my explanation of magicks.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Let us review. Like units, magicks have a{Newline}
charge time requirement and a Speed attribute.{Newline}
{Newline}
Keep in mind the amount of time required to{Newline}
cast magicks when choosing one.{Newline}
{Newline}
When casting a magick, you must select a target{Newline}
within its range. The magick will affect all{Newline}
tiles in its area of effect.{Newline}
You may choose to cast a magick on either a{Newline}
unit or a tile.{Newline}
{Newline}
If you cast a magick on a unit, the magick's{Newline}
area of effect will move along with the{Newline}
targeted unit.{Newline}
If you cast a magick on a tile and there are no{Newline}
units within the area of effect when the magick{Newline}
is finally cast, the magick will be wasted.{Newline}
Keep these points in mind to make the most{Newline}
of your units' magicks.{Newline}
{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
Understanding these concepts should allow you{Newline}
to gain the upper hand in any battle you fight.{Newline}
{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
Every time the CT gauge goes up, it increases{Newline}
by an amount equal to the unit's Speed.{Newline}
{Newline}
This means that units with a high Speed will{Newline}
see their CT gauges fill up more quickly.
{MClose}
If the attack was successful, the unit will gain{Newline}
experience points (EXP) and job points (JP).{Newline}
{Newline}
After a unit has both moved and acted, {Newline}
his or her turn will automatically end.{Newline}
{Newline}
When a unit's turn ends, you must choose his or{Newline}
her facing. This affects the probability of him{Newline}
or her dodging enemy attacks.{Newline}
You will want to be facing the enemy whenever{Newline}
possible.
{MClose}
This concludes my explanation of{Newline}
movement and actions.{Newline}
{Newline}
You will be repeating these steps many times{Newline}
as you battle your foes.{Newline}
{Newline}
This is one of the fundamentals of battle, so{Newline}
please do your best to remember what you{Newline}
have learned here.{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
