{event text}
{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session, we shall discuss status effects.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Status effects are indicated by a variety of{Newline}
cues, such as the color of a unit or a balloon{Newline}
above the unit's head.
{MClose}
You may see all status effects currently{Newline}
affecting a unit by looking at his or her status{Newline}
screen.
{MClose}
A status effect refers to a variety of{Newline}
conditions that may affect a unit on the{Newline}
battlefield.{Newline}
In general, these may be divided into four{Newline}
groups: beneficial statuses, status ailments,{Newline}
physical states, and action states.{Newline}
Firstly, let us discuss the various action states{Newline}
a unit may be in as a result of using abilities.
{MClose}
There are 3 different action states: charging,{Newline}
performing, and defending.{Newline}
{Newline}
These states are generally canceled once the{Newline}
unit's next turn arrives, or when an ability{Newline}
goes into effect.
{MClose}
The magick has been cast, so the black mage's{Newline}
charging state has now been canceled.{Newline}
{Newline}
Next, I shall explain beneficial statuses.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
A beneficial status is a positive effect that is{Newline}
brought about by an ability or spell.{Newline}
{Newline}
These may gradually restore the unit's HP,{Newline}
or increase the unit's Speed attribute.
{MClose}
For example, the Protect magick increases a{Newline}
unit's resistance to physical attacks.{Newline}
{Newline}
Thus, the affected unit will take less damage{Newline}
from physical attacks.{Newline}
{Newline}
There are many other beneficial statuses.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Beneficial statuses may be removed by means{Newline}
of the mystic's Harmony ability.
{MClose}
Next, we shall discuss status ailments.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
These negative statuses include curses or{Newline}
magick effects that adversely affect a unit.{Newline}
{Newline}
These may cause the unit to act randomly,{Newline}
be unable to move or act, or have its HP{Newline}
gradually drained.
{MClose}
One example of this is the Blind status.{Newline}
When blinded, a unit's chance of striking a{Newline}
blow in combat is decreased.{Newline}
There are many other types of status{Newline}
ailments.
{MClose}
If the effect of a status ailment is adversely{Newline}
affecting a unit's performance in battle, it is{Newline}
best to remove it.{Newline}
Status ailments may be removed by using a{Newline}
remedy, or with the white magick Esuna.
{MClose}
However, these may not be effective against{Newline}
all status ailments.{Newline}
{Newline}
There are additional ways of removing status{Newline}
ailments as well.{Newline}
{Newline}
For example, a unit who has been turned to{Newline}
stone may also be restored by using a{Newline}
gold needle.{Newline}
However, a unit who has been turned undead{Newline}
may only be restored by using holy water.{Newline}
{Newline}
For more information about how to remove{Newline}
status effects, refer to the quick help{Newline}
descriptions.
{MClose}
Lastly, allow me to explain about physical{Newline}
states.{Newline}
{Newline}
There are two physical states: Critical and{Newline}
KO.
{MClose}
A critically wounded unit may have his or{Newline}
her HP restored with the white magick Cure{Newline}
or with a potion.{Newline}
A KO'd unit may be revived with the white{Newline}
magick Raise or with phoenix down.
{MClose}
The Critical state has no particular adverse{Newline}
effects on a unit, but a KO'd unit cannot{Newline}
act on his or her own.{Newline}
Prepare in advance to keep your units from{Newline}
being KO'd.{Newline}
{Newline}
It is always advisable to bring at least one{Newline}
unit with abilities that allow it to heal or{Newline}
revive other units.{Newline}
If you do not revive a KO'd unit within a{Newline}
certain amount of time, its body will{Newline}
disappear.{Newline}
In its place, a treasure chest or crystal will{Newline}
appear.{Newline}
{Newline}
Once a unit has disappeared in this way,{Newline}
reviving him or her will be impossible.{Newline}
The unit is gone forever.{Newline}
Crystals and treasure chests left behind{Newline}
by KO'd units may be obtained by moving{Newline}
units onto the tiles they occupy.{Newline}
Treasure chests contain items.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
Crystals restore a unit's HP and MP.{Newline}
{Newline}
{Newline}
In some cases, crystals allow the units that{Newline}
obtain them to acquire the abilities of{Newline}
the units who left them behind.{Newline}
The units will instantly learn the new{Newline}
abilities without having to spend job{Newline}
points.
{MClose}
This concludes my discussion of status{Newline}
effects.{Newline}
{Newline}
Always do your best to use items and{Newline}
white magicks to prevent your units from{Newline}
being KO'd.{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
