{Color 08}Master Darlavon{Newline}
{Color 00}Now then, let us begin the lesson.{Newline}
{Newline}
In this session, I shall explain how to change{Newline}
the game options and what each option means.{Newline}
{Newline}
You may use the options menu to change a{Newline}
variety of game settings.{Newline}
{Newline}
The options menu may be accessed both from{Newline}
the world map and from the battlefield.{Newline}
{Newline}
On the battlefield, press △ in free cursor{Newline}
mode to open the menu.{Newline}
{Newline}
First, press ○ to close the battle menu and{Newline}
enter free cursor mode.
{MClose}
You are now in free cursor mode. In this{Newline}
mode, you may freely move the cursor{Newline}
using the directional buttons.{Newline}
Now press △ to open the menu, and{Newline}
select "Options."
{MClose}
This is the options menu.{Newline}
Let us examine each option.{Newline}
{Newline}
1. Cursor Movement lets you change{Newline}
how the cursor moves on the battlefield.
{MClose}
With Type A, pressing the up button{Newline}
moves the cursor toward the upper{Newline}
right.{Newline}
With Type B, pressing the up button{Newline}
moves the cursor toward the upper left.
{MClose}
2. Cursor Repeat Rate controls how quickly{Newline}
the cursor moves across the battlefield.
{MClose}
3. Multi-height Toggle Rate controls how{Newline}
quickly the cursor moves between two levels,{Newline}
such as tiles on and below a bridge.
{MClose}
Selecting "Off" will prevent the cursor from{Newline}
moving automatically. Instead, you must press{Newline}
START to switch levels.
{MClose}
4. Menu Cursor Speed controls the speed{Newline}
of the finger cursor when moving through{Newline}
menus.
{MClose}
5. Message Speed allows you to{Newline}
adjust the display speed of dialogue{Newline}
and system messages.
{MClose}
6. Battle Prompts allows you to toggle{Newline}
the display of messages during battle{Newline}
that explain the game controls.
{MClose}
7. Display Ability Names controls whether{Newline}
ability and magick names are displayed when{Newline}
they are used.
{MClose}
8. Display Effect Messages controls whether{Newline}
the effects of actions are displayed.
{MClose}
9. Display Earned EXP/JP controls{Newline}
whether experience and job points obtained{Newline}
by units are displayed on-screen during battle.
{MClose}
10. Target Colors controls whether enemies{Newline}
and allies are highlighted in different{Newline}
colors when selecting a target.{Newline}
This makes it easier to distinguish between{Newline}
allies and enemies.
{MClose}
11. Display Unequippable Items affects which{Newline}
items are displayed when equipping a unit.{Newline}
{Newline}
If this is set to "Off," items that cannot be{Newline}
equipped by a certain unit will not be included{Newline}
in the item list for that unit.
{MClose}
12. Optimize on Job Change affects the{Newline}
items equipped on a unit when changing his{Newline}
or her job or assigning new abilities.{Newline}
When this option is turned on, the strongest{Newline}
equipment will be automatically selected for a{Newline}
unit when his or her job or abilities change.
{MClose}
13. Sound controls whether sound effects{Newline}
and music should be played in mono, stereo,{Newline}
or surround modes.
{MClose}
14. Restore Default Settings allows you{Newline}
to restore all options to their default{Newline}
values by selecting "Defaults."
{MClose}
This concludes my explanation of the game{Newline}
options.{Newline}
{Newline}
Try to find the settings you like best to make{Newline}
your gaming experience as comfortable as{Newline}
possible.{Newline}
With that, I shall bring this lesson to a close.
{MClose}
